{
  "texts": [
    "In this study, we employed short molecular dynamics (MD) simulations as a rapid screening method to qualitatively assess the ionic conductivity of generated polymers against those in the training set.",
    "MD simulations were performed using the PCFF+ 57, a classical non-polarizable force field, to directly compare the conductivity across both sets.",
    "Although this approach enables the efficient evaluation of a large number of polymer candidates, the 5 ns production runs used may not fully capture the longterm dynamics required for equilibration, particularly in low-conductivity polymers.",
    "Previous studies 10 have demonstrated that longer simulation times, such as 50 ns runs, yield more reliable conductivity estimates, especially for polymers with slower ion diffusion.",
    "While experimental validation remains the ultimate benchmark for real-world performance, the integration of more advanced MD workflows-such as classical polarizable or machine-learned force fields combined with extended simulation timeswould further enhance the accuracy and efficiency of the screening process."
  ]
}